programme.title: Lip-Reading the Royals: What Are They Really Saying?
programme.desc: Little Prince Louis has stolen the nation's hearts, but there's more to the loveable rogue than cute waves and cheeky grins. Watch as he causes enough chaos at a Christmas church service that both Prince William and King Charles are left apologising to the vicar. When Trump came to town, the world's press would have done anything to be a fly on the wall. Now they don't have to wonder. Our lip-readers decode what they believe the president said to Kate and the moment William stepped in to save the day. No royal is making more headlines right now than Andrew. His appearance at the Duchess of Kent's funeral sparked a frenzy of speculation, particularly that tense, loaded encounter with William. Now, for the first time, our lip readers reveal what they believe was actually being said. And with Andrew firmly in the firing line, sisters Beatrice and Eugenie were spotted deep in conversation on the streets of Mayfair. It made front pages around the world. But what were they really saying? Series Prod: Ben Algar; Exec Prod: Jonathan Levi; Dirs: Ben Algar/Jason Davidson/Pete Roch; Content Kings (S1 Ep2)

programme.title: The Three Kings of 1936
programme.desc: This documentary marks the 90th anniversary of one of the most extraordinary and turbulent years in the history of the British royal family - a year that still casts a long shadow. A fast-paced, chronological story plunges viewers into the whirlwind of events in 1936: the death of George V, the brief reign and unprecedented abdication of Edward VIII, and the reluctant rise of George VI. The abdication can be seen as the first modern worldwide scandal, when Victorian attitudes clashed with 20th century morals. But 1936 is more than just a royal soap opera - the programme explores the motivations of those at the heart of the story, and gauges the impact on the average Briton, unaware of the King's dilemma until the last few days. Narrated by Tracy-Ann Oberman.
